This paper deals with object detection in adverse weather conditions, which is a common problem in computer vision. The proposed method involves using prior knowledge of the physics of image formation to define a novel prior-adversarial loss, which is a technique commonly used in computer vision and machine learning. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also involves training a model to adapt to different weather conditions, which is a problem of domain adaptation, and hence, it could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also involves using unsupervised learning techniques, which could place it in the category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also involves using residual feature recovery blocks, which is a technique commonly used in robotics, and hence, it could belong to cs.RO (Robotics). Finally, the paper involves evaluating the proposed method on different datasets, which is a common practice in multimedia research, and hence, it could belong to cs.MM (Multimedia).
